title: BrepType Enumeration
summary: Shape catalog renewal makes it possible to organize shapes in the shape catalog compared to a plain list before. Thus, it is now possible and required to distinguish shapes in such a manner that: BuildingProduct represent shapes that users can import from, for example, Tekla Warehouse and insert them into a model. These are usually provided by the manufacturer and not detailed by users themselves. StructuralShape represent shapes that get created by "Convert part to item" or from geometry editing.
description: Shape catalog renewal makes it possible to organize shapes in the shape catalog compared to a plain list before.

title: ShapeItem.Fingerprint Property
summary: A fingerprint value calculated by Tekla Structures to provide quick comparison of geometries to avoid inserting same shape multiple times to the catalog. More rigorous comparison is done only for geometries that result in identical fingerprints.
description: A fingerprint value calculated by Tekla Structures to provide quick comparison of geometries to avoid inserting same shape multiple times to the catalog. More rigorous comparison is done only for geometries that result in identical fingerprints.

title: ShapeItem.GeometryGuid Property
summary: A unique identifier of the shape geometry, given initially by BrepStorage. This GUID is used as the body of the filename for the shape geometry information found in the ShapeGeometries directory
description: A unique identifier of the shape geometry, given initially by BrepStorage. This GUID is used as the body of the filename for the shape geometry information found in the ShapeGeometries directory

title: ShapeItem.GeometryHash Property
summary: This obsolete property can still be used to store and externally provided unique hash value identifying the shape. However, Tekla Structures does not use this value internally for anything. It is strongly recommended to use the newer Fingerprint property for future implementations. That value is automatically calculated by Tekla Structures for all inserted shapes and is used internally for shape identification.
description: This obsolete property can still be used to store and externally provided unique hash value identifying the shape. However, Tekla Structures does not use this value internally for anything.

title: ShapeItem.Guid Property
summary: A unique identifier of the actual shape, given initially by the ShapeCatalog. This GUID is used as the body of the filename for the shape information found in the Shape directory
description: A unique identifier of the actual shape, given initially by the ShapeCatalog. This GUID is used as the body of the filename for the shape information found in the Shape directory

title: ShapeItem.HandlePoints Property
summary: Defines handle points of the shape.
description: Defines handle points of the shape.

title: ShapeItem.IsSolid Property
summary: Set to true if the shape is detected by TS Core to be a valid solid
description: Set to true if the shape is detected by TS Core to be a valid solid

title: ShapeItem.Name Property
summary: The shape Name
description: The shape Name

title: ShapeItem.ShapeFacetedBrep Property
summary: The data structure containing the geometric information of the shape as a FacetedBRep
description: The data structure containing the geometric information of the shape as a FacetedBRep

title: ShapeItem.UpAxis Property
summary: The direction defining what is understood as "up" in the shape that the API user is providing. Typically this is the z-axis, if the data is in global coordinates, coming from a system where Z-axis points to global up direction. Possible values are: Undefined = 0, X_Axis = 1, Y_Axis = 2, Z_Axis = 3. It is highly recommendable to orient shapes in the Tekla Structures native way, that is x-axis on the extrusion line and Y-axis pointing up. NOTE: Specifying UpAxis to be ShapeUpAxis.Undefined may throw a System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException exception in certain operations, because the system can not proceed without that information.
description: The direction defining what is understood as "up" in the shape that the API user is providing. Typically this is the z-axis, if the data is in global coordinates, coming from a system where Z-axis points to global up direction.
